  <span id="freeText7255069317452134985" style="display:none">Early in the book, I mean page four, Bruce Robertson farts and walks away to blame it on someone else. Even earlier, I mean page two, someone gets their head smashed in with a hammer. The attention to detail is repulsive.<br /><br />Can you stomach this sort of thing for 392 pages?<br /><br />Author Irvine Welsh composed a perversely compelling character: Robertson is a cop, but he is the kind of cop who doesn't want to get involved in a murder investigation because his vacation is coming up soon. He's already booked the ticket, he explains. His body is covered in rashes and sores and full of worms. His mind is just as disgusting. We get to explore both, in all their grossness. Welsh gets creative with formatting (some might consider it gimmicky) but it's new and unique and adds a little extra "oomph" into the narrative, which was already intriguing on its own.<br /><br />3 stars out of 5.</span>
